image.altText: Five Dutch players celebrate a goal against the USA at the Women's World Cup.

items.synopsis: As Australia prepares to cheer on the Matildas tonight, the USA and Netherlands face off across the Tasman in a much-anticipated encounter. Follow live.

title.children: Netherlands lead USA in blockbuster World Cup clash

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: What a monumental scoreline. Is the USA's air of invulnerability about the be breached? The Americans had the early run of play, and it was virtually the first chance for the Dutch that they put away, but since that point they have certainly matched their opponents. If anything I think they had the better half. They did well to break up play with some tactical fouling, and have frustrated the US midfield, who can't get any flow going. The USA need the get the ball to Sophia Smith more frequently, and I wouldn't be surprised if we see Rose Lavelle on at half time. The US, winners of the last two World Cups, look rattled.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: HALF-TIME: USA 0 - 1 Netherlands

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Fortescue Metals says it shipped a record 192 million tonnes of iron ore over the 2023 financial year, including 48.9 million tonnes over the fourth quarter. The company says its the fourth year in a row of record shipments. It expects to ship up to 197 million tonnes of the steel making material over the 2024 financial year, including from its new Iron Bridge mine in the Pilbara. Here's Fortescue chief executive Fiona Hicks: "Our hematite operations are performing strongly and we are focused on delivering growth through the safe and efficient ramp up of Iron Bridge, unlocking the potential of Belinga (Iron Ore Project in Gabon) and decarbonising our iron ore operations." FMG says it sold iron ore for an average price of $US94.74 a dry metric ton over the 2023 financial year, 14 per cent lower than the average benchmark price of $US109.60 a dry metric ton. FMG shares are down 0.5 per cent to $23.59 in morning trade.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: FMG sees record annual iron ore shipments

children.content: Fortescue Metals says it shipped a record 192 million tonnes of iron ore over the 2023 financial year, including 48.9 million tonnes over the fourth quarter.
The company says its the fourth year in a row of record shipments.
It expects to ship up to 197 million tonnes of the steel making material over the 2024 financial year, including from its new Iron Bridge mine in the Pilbara.
Here's Fortescue chief executive Fiona Hicks:

"Our hematite operations are performing strongly and we are focused on delivering growth through the safe and efficient ramp up of Iron Bridge, unlocking the potential of Belinga (Iron Ore Project in Gabon) and decarbonising our iron ore operations."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The price of wholesale energy has more than halved since this time last year according to the latest report from the Australian Energy Market Operator. The AEMO says wholesale spot prices averaged $108 per megawatt hour over the June quarter, down 59 per cent from last year's record-high power prices which led to the temporary suspension of the energy market. However, the energy operator says prices have risen by one-third since the March quarter. The AEMO says prices are being pushed down thanks to more wind and solar and also more power from coal fired generators in New South Wales. AEMO chief executive Daniel Westerman told RN Breakfast that the energy market is no longer as volatile.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Wholesale energy prices down 60 per cent

featuredLink.title: AEMO releases latest energy report - ABC Radio National

children.content: The price of wholesale energy has more than halved since this time last year according to the latest report from the Australian Energy Market Operator.

The AEMO says wholesale spot prices averaged $108 per megawatt hour over the June quarter, down 59 per cent from last year's record-high power prices which led to the temporary suspension of the energy market.
However, the energy operator says prices have risen by one-third since the March quarter.
The AEMO says prices are being pushed down thanks to more wind and solar and also more power from coal fired generators in New South Wales.
AEMO chief executive Daniel Westerman told RN Breakfast that the energy market is no longer as volatile.
